            <h1>Plant Based Diet</h1>

            <h2>What is a plant based diet?</h2>
            <p>
                A plant-based diet is a way of eating that emphasizes foods derived from plants, such as fruits,
                vegetables, whole grains, legumes, nuts, and seeds. While there are different variations of plant-based
                diets, they all prioritize foods that come from plant sources rather than animal sources.

                <br>
                <br>

                Plant-based diets may or may not exclude animal products altogether. For example, a vegan diet is a type
                of plant-based diet that excludes all animal products, including meat, dairy, eggs, and honey. On the
                other hand, a vegetarian diet may include some animal products, such as dairy and eggs, but excludes
                meat.
                <br>
                <br>
                Research has shown that a plant-based diet can offer a range of health benefits, including lower risk of
                heart disease, type 2 diabetes, and certain cancers. It may also be more environmentally sustainable
                than diets that are heavy in animal products, as plant-based foods tend to have a lower carbon
                footprint.

                <br>
                <br>
                Overall, a plant-based diet can be a healthy and sustainable way of eating that prioritizes whole,
                nutrient-dense foods while minimizing or eliminating processed and animal-based foods.

            </p>

            <h2>Benefits of a plant based diet</h2>
            <p>
                Provide an example of a plant-based diet.
            <ol class="list">
                <li>
                    Improved overall health:
                    <p>
                        Plant-based diets have been linked to a lower risk of chronic diseases, such as heart disease,
                        type 2 diabetes, certain cancers, and hypertension. They can also promote healthy weight
                        management and improve overall gut health.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    Lower risk of heart disease:
                    <p>
                        Plant-based diets have been shown to reduce the risk of heart disease, as they are typically
                        lower in saturated and trans fats, which can contribute to elevated cholesterol levels.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    Improved digestion:
                    <p>
                        Plant-based diets are rich in fiber, which can promote regular bowel movements and improve
                        overall gut health.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    Increased energy
                    <p>
                        A diet high in whole plant foods can provide sustained energy throughout the day, without the
                        energy spikes and crashes that can come from consuming highly processed foods.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    Better environmental sustainability
                    <p>
                        Plant-based diets have a lower carbon footprint than diets that are heavy in animal products, as
                        raising and processing animal products requires significantly more resources, including land,
                        water, and energy.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    Lower healthcare costs:
                    <p>
                        Lower healthcare costs: A plant-based diet can help prevent chronic diseases and reduce
                        healthcare costs associated with these conditions.
                    </p>
                </li>


            </ol>
            </p>

